*[http://purl.umn.edu/107353 Oral history interview with Martin Hellman] Oral history interview 2004, Palo Alto, California. [[Charles_Babbage_Institute|Charles Babbage Institute]], University of Minnesota, Minneapolis. Hellman describes his invention of [[public_key_cryptography|public key cryptography]] with collaborators [[Whitfield_Diffie|Whitfield Diffie]] and [[Ralph_Merkle|Ralph Merkle]] at Stanford University in the mid-1970s. He also relates his subsequent work in cryptography with [[Steve_Pohlig|Steve Pohlig]] (the [[Pohlig–Hellman_algorithm|Pohlig–Hellman algorithm]]) and others. Hellman addresses the [[National_Security_Agency|National Security Agency]]’s (NSA) early efforts to contain and discourage academic work in the field, the Department of Commerce’s encryption export restrictions (under the [[ITAR|International Traffic of Arms Regulation]], or ITAR), and key escrow (the so-called [[Clipper_chip|Clipper chip]]). He also touches on the commercialization of cryptography with [[RSA_Data_Security|RSA Data Security]] and [[VeriSign|VeriSign]].
